From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000076 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Julien Etienne <julien.etienne@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, 14 Jul 2026 16:24:00 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] arm64: dts: gemini: fix AW9523 matrix polarity

The Planet vendor AW9523 scan drives the selected column physically low,
drives inactive columns physically high, and treats a low row level as a
pressed key.  Linux's gpio-matrix-keypad already models this state machine:
gpio-activelow inverts logical GPIO values; drive-inactive-cols keeps
non-selected columns driven instead of changing them to inputs.

Keep the keyboard and expander disabled.  This correction makes the
candidate scan electrically faithful without claiming that the AW9523 GPIO
range, reset,
interrupt, debounce, rollover, wake, or keymap behavior has been validated;
hardware evidence is still required.

Signed-off-by: Julien Etienne <julien.etienne@gmail.com>
---
 arch/arm64/boot/dts/mediatek/mt6797-gemini-pda.dts | 2 ++
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)

diff --git a/arch/arm64/boot/dts/mediatek/mt6797-gemini-pda.dts b/arch/arm64/boot/dts/mediatek/mt6797-gemini-pda.dts
--- a/arch/arm64/boot/dts/mediatek/mt6797-gemini-pda.dts
+++ b/arch/arm64/boot/dts/mediatek/mt6797-gemini-pda.dts
@@ -285,6 +285,8 @@
 	keyboard-matrix {
 		compatible = "gpio-matrix-keypad";
 		pinctrl-names = "default";
+		gpio-activelow;
+		drive-inactive-cols;
 		pinctrl-0 = <&keyboard_matrix_row_pins
 				     &keyboard_matrix_col_pins>;
 		row-gpios = <&aw9523 0 GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH>,
-- 
